      'paper1': "Page 1 of 12                       \n \n \n  \n   \n \n \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2013 \n \nEnglish ‚Äď Higher Level ‚Äď Paper I \n \n \nTotal Marks: 200 \n \nWednesday, 5th June ‚Äď Morning, 9.30 ‚Äď 12.20  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ This paper is divided into two sections,  \nSection I COMPREHENDING and Section II COMPOSING. \nÔā∑ The paper contains three  texts on the general th eme of STORY-TELLING. \nÔā∑ Candidates should familiarise themselves w ith each of the texts before beginning \ntheir answers.  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ Both sections of this paper (COMPR EHENDING and COMP OSING) must be \nattempted.  \nÔā∑ Each section carries 100 marks.  \n \n \n \nSECTION I ‚Äď COMPREHENDING \n \nÔā∑ Two Questions, A and B, follow each text.  \nÔā∑ Candidates must answer a Question A on one text and a Question B on a different \ntext.  Candidates must answer only one Question A and only one Question B.  \nÔā∑ N.B.  Candidates may NOT answer a Ques tion A and a Question B on the same \ntext.  \n \n \n \n \nSECTION II ‚Äď COMPOSING \n \nÔā∑ Candidates must write on one of the compositions 1 ‚Äď 7. \n \n \n  Coimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \n \n   2013.  M.11 \n\nPage 2 of 12 SECTION 1                       COMPREHENDING                        (100 marks) \nTEXT 1 \n \nThis edited text is based on an article, entitled, Tune in Next Week ‚Äď The Curious Staying Power of \nthe Cliff-hanger .  It was  written by Emily Nussbaum for The New Yorker magazine.  \n \n \n \n \n \n  \n \nNarrowly defined, a cliff-hanger is a climax \ncracked in half: the bomb ticks, the screen goes \nblack.  A lady wriggles on train tracks ‚Äď will \nanyone save her?  Italics on a black screen: ‚ÄúTo \nbe continued‚Ä¶‚ÄĚ More broadly, it‚Äôs any strong \ndose of ‚ÄúWhat happens ne xt?‚ÄĚ‚Äď the question that \nhovers in the black space between episodes.  In \nthe digital age, that gap is an accordion: it might \nbe a week or eight months; it might arrive at the \nend of an episode or as a season finale. Cliff-\nhangers are the point when the audience decides \nto keep buying.  They are sensational in every \nsense of the word.  Historically there‚Äôs something \nsuspect about a story told in this manner, the way \nit tugs the customer to the next ledge.  Nobody \nlikes needy. \n \nBut there is also something to celebrate about the \ncliff-hanger.  It makes visible the storyteller‚Äôs \nconnection to his audien ce ‚Äď like a bridge made \nout of lightning. Primal and unashamedly \nmanipulative, cliff-hangers are the signature \ngambit of serial storytelli ng.  They reveal that a \nstory is artificial , then dare you to keep believing. \nIf you trust the creator, you take that dare, and \nkeep going. \n \nTelevision is just a Johnny-come-lately when it \ncomes to episodic storytelling. The great \nnineteenth-century novels were famous for their \ncliff-hangers.  Many people associate the form \nwith Charles Dickens, who wrote serial novels so \ncomplex, yet so rewarding, that one might even \nsay they resemble the TV show, The Wire. \nPrinted episodically in magazines, Dickens‚Äô cliff-\nhangers triggered desperat ion i",
