      'paper1': "Page 1 of 12                       \n \n \n  \n   \n \n \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2014 \n \nEnglish ‚Äď Higher Level ‚Äď Paper I \n \n \nTotal Marks: 200 \n \nWednesday, 4th June ‚Äď Morning, 9.30 ‚Äď 12.20  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ This paper is divided into two sections,  \nSection I COMPREHENDING and Section II COMPOSING. \nÔā∑ The paper contains three  texts on the general theme of INFLUENCE. \nÔā∑ Candidates should familiarise themselves w ith each of the texts before beginning \ntheir answers.  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ Both sections of this paper (COMPR EHENDING and COMP OSING) must be \nattempted.  \nÔā∑ Each section carries 100 marks.  \n \n \n \nSECTION I ‚Äď COMPREHENDING \n \nÔā∑ Two Questions, A and B, follow each text.  \nÔā∑ Candidates must answer a Question A on one text and a Question B on a different \ntext.  Candidates must answer only one Question A and only one Question B.  \nÔā∑ N.B.  Candidates may NOT answer a Ques tion A and a Question B on the same \ntext.  \n \n \n \n \nSECTION II ‚Äď COMPOSING \n \nÔā∑ Candidates must write on one of the compositions 1 ‚Äď 7. \n \n \n  \n  Coimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \n \n   2014.  M.11 \n\nPage 2 of 12 SECTION 1                        COMPREHENDING                       (100 marks) \n                                               TEXT 1 \n \n \nAN INFLUENTIAL EVENT \n \nIn the novel, Canada , Richard Ford tells how a bank robber y committed b y Bev and Neeva \nParsons influenced the lives of their children, De ll and his twin sister, Berner, who were fifteen \nyears old at the time of the crime.  In this ed ited extract Dell remembers his escape to Canada \nwith his mother‚Äôs friend, Mildred Remlinger.\n \nFirst, I‚Äôll tell about th e robbery our parents \ncommitted.  Then about the murders, which \nhappened later.  The robbery is the more \nimportant part, since it served to set my and my \nsister‚Äôs lives on the courses they eventually \nfollowed.  Nothing would make complete sense \nwithout that bei ng told first. \n \nOur parents were the l east likely two people in \nthe world to rob a bank.  They weren‚Äôt strange \npeople, not obviously criminals.  No one \nwould‚Äôve thought they were destined to end up \nthe way they did.  They were just regular ‚Äď \nalthough, of course, that kind of thinking became \nnull and void the moment they did rob a bank... \n \nMildred Remlinger drove up to our house in her \nbattered old brown Ford, came straight up the \nwalk, up the steps and knocked on the front door, \nbehind which I was waiting alone.  She came \nright inside and told me to pack my bag. She \nasked where my sister Berner was. I told her \nshe‚Äôd left the day before. Mildred said we didn‚Äôt \nhave time to go and look for her. Juvenile \nofficials representing the State of Montana would \nbe coming soon to take us into custody. It was a \nmiracle, she said, they hadn‚Äôt come already. Then \nwith me in the car seat beside her, Mildred drove \nus out of Great Falls that  late morning of August \n30, 1960, and straight nort h up the 87 highway. \n \nMildred didn‚Äôt much speak at first, as Great Fal",
      'paper2': "                                                                                                                                                                                  Page 1 of 8                                                                                                                              20 14.  M.12 \n \nCoimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \n \n  \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2014 \n \nEnglish - Higher Level - Paper 2 \n \nTotal Marks: 200 \n \nThursday, 5th June ‚Äď Afternoo n, 2.00 ‚Äď 5.20 \n  \n \nCandidates must attempt the following: \nÔā∑ ONE   question from SECTION I ‚Äď The Single Text \nÔā∑ ONE   question from SECTION II ‚Äď The Comparative Study \nÔā∑ ONE   question on the Unseen Poem from SECTION III ‚Äď Poetry \nÔā∑ ONE   question on Prescribed Poetry from SECTION III ‚Äď Poetry \n \nN.B.  Candidates must answer on Shakespearean Drama. \nThey may do so in SECTION I, the Single Text ( Macbeth)  or in SECTION II,  \nThe Comparative Study ( Macbeth, Othello ). \n \n \n \n \n \nINDEX OF SINGLE TEXTS \nPride and Prejudice ÔÄ≠ Page 2   \nEmpire of the Sun ÔÄ≠ Page 2 \nTranslations ÔÄ≠ Page 3 \nNever Let Me Go     ÔÄ≠ Page 3 \nMacbeth  ÔÄ≠ Page 3 \n \n   \n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                  Page 2 of 8 SECTION I                     THE SINGLE TEXT                   (60 marks) \n \nCandidates must answer one question from this section ( A ‚Äď E ). \n \n \nA PRIDE AND PREJUDICE  ‚Äď Jane Austen \n \n \n(i) ‚ÄúReaders can both admire Elizabeth Bennet‚Äôs character  and learn a variety of \n lessons from her experiences.‚ÄĚ  \n  \n To what extent do you agree with this vi ew?  Support your answ er with su itable  \n   reference to the novel, Pride and Prejudice . \n \nOR \n \n(ii) ‚ÄúThroughout the novel, Pride and Prejudice , Austen uses a vari ety of techniques \nto entertain her readers an d provide commentary on the society of her day.‚ÄĚ \n \n Discuss this view of the novel, supporting  your answer with su itable reference to \nthe text. \n   \n \n \nB EMPIRE OF THE SUN  ‚Äď J. G. Ballard \n \n \n(i) ‚ÄúDespite his experiences throughout the story, in many ways Jim‚Äôs character \nremains unchanged.‚ÄĚ  \n \n  To what extent do  you agree or disagree with this view of the character of Jim \n Graham?  Support your answ er with suitable referen ce to Ballard‚Äôs novel,   \n   Empire of the Sun . \n \nOR \n \n(ii)  ‚ÄúIn the novel, Empire of the Sun , Ballard presents reader s with both horror and \nhumanity to create a comp elling account of war.‚ÄĚ \n                 \n  Discuss this view of the novel, supporti ng your answer with suitable reference to \nthe text. \n \n     \n\n                                                                                                                                                                                  Page 3 of 8  \n \nD NEVER LET ME GO ‚Äď  Kazuo Ishiguro  \n   \n(i) ‚ÄúReaders of Never Let Me Go  can have difficulty sympathising wit",
