      'paper1': "Page 1 of 12                       \n \n \n  \n   \n \n \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2016 \n \nEnglish ‚Äď Higher Level ‚Äď Paper I \n \n \nTotal Marks: 200 \n \nWednesday, 8th June ‚Äď Morning, 9.30 ‚Äď 12.20  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ This paper is divided into two sections,  \nSection I COMPREHENDING and Section II COMPOSING. \nÔā∑ The paper contains three  texts on the general theme of JOURNEYS.  \nÔā∑ Candidates should familiarise themselves w ith each of the texts before beginning \ntheir answers.  \n \n \n \nÔā∑ Both sections of this paper (COMPR EHENDING and COMP OSING) must be \nattempted.  \nÔā∑ Each section carries 100 marks.  \n \n \n \nSECTION I ‚Äď COMPREHENDING \n \nÔā∑ Two Questions, A and B, follow each text.  \nÔā∑ Candidates must answer a Question A on one text and a Question B on a different \ntext.  Candidates must answer only one Question A and only one Question B.  \nÔā∑ N.B.  Candidates may NOT answer a Ques tion A and a Question B on the same \ntext.  \n \n \n \n \nSECTION II ‚Äď COMPOSING \n \nÔā∑ Candidates must write on one of the compositions 1 ‚Äď 7. \n \n \n  Coimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \n \n   2016  M.11 \n\nPage 2 of 12  \n \nTEXT 1 ‚Äď A DRAMATIC JOURNEY \n \nThis text consists of both visual images and an ed ited written extract.  The written text is adapted \nfrom Andrew Dickson‚Äôs book, Worlds Elsewhere ‚Äď Journeys Around Shakespeare‚Äôs Globe . \n \n \n SECTION 1                  COMPREHENDING               (100 marks ) \n\nPage 3 of 12                      N.B.   Candidates may NOT answer Questi on A and Question B on the same text.  \n \nQuestions A and B carry 50 marks each. \n \nQUESTION A \n \n(i)  Outline, in your own words, the insights Andr ew Dickson shares about Sh akespeare‚Äôs play     \n The Comedy of Errors  in the written text above.  (15)             \n \n(ii)  From the four posters in the above text, choose the poster th at you think is most effective in\n advertising a production of the play, The Comedy of Errors .  Explain your choice  with reference  \n to the written text and the conten t and visual appeal of the poster.                                         (15)             \n \n(iii)  The writer suggests that Shakespeare‚Äôs plays have timeless and global qualities.  Do you agree \n with this view?  Support your an swer with reference to the abov e text (written and visual) and \n your own experience of at least one  Shakespearean drama, other than The Comedy of Errors .   \n You may refer to written texts, stag e productions or films.                                                          (20)             \n \n \nQUESTION B   \n \nImagine that you are the adjudicator for a poster competition; entries must promote a production of \nShakespeare‚Äôs play, The Comedy of Errors to a contemporary audience.  The entries on Page 2 represent \nthe finalists in the competition.  Write a  speech  in which you announce the first and second prize \nwinners.  In your speech you should explain your judge ment, commenting on the visual appeal of the \nfirst and second prize winning entries and thei",
      'paper2': " \n                                                                                                                                                                                  Page 1 of 8           \nCoimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \n \n  \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2016 \n \nEnglish - Higher Level - Paper 2 \n \nTotal Marks: 200 \n \nThursday, 9th June ‚Äď Afternoon, 2.00 ‚Äď 5.20  \n  \n \nCandidates must attempt the following : \nÔā∑ ONE   question from SECTION I ‚Äď The Single Text \nÔā∑ ONE   question from SECTION II ‚Äď The Comparative Study \nÔā∑ ONE   question on the Unseen Po em from SECTION III ‚Äď Poetry \nÔā∑ ONE   question on Prescribed Poet ry from SECTION III ‚Äď Poetry \n \nN.B.  Candidates must answer on Shakespearean Drama. \nThey may do so in SECTION I, the Single Text ( King Lear)  or in SECTION II, The  \nComparative Study ( King Lear , Othello ). \n \n \n \n \n \nINDEX OF SINGLE TEXTS \nWuthering Heights ÔÄ≠ Page 2   \nThe Great Gatsby ÔÄ≠ Page 2 \nTranslations ÔÄ≠ Page 2 \nDeath and Nightingales ÔÄ≠ Page 3  \nKing Lear ÔÄ≠ Page 3 \n 2016.   M.12 \n\n\n \n                                                                                                                                                                                  Page 2 of 8  SECTION I                     THE SINGLE TEXT                   (60 marks) \n \nCandidates must answer one question from this section ( A ‚Äď E ). \n \nA WUTHERING HEIGHTS ‚Äď Emily Bront√ę  \n \n(i)   ‚ÄúCatherine Earnshaw and Heathcliff share a variety of character traits that \ncontribute to the dramatic and tragic aspects of the story.‚ÄĚ \n \nTo what extent do  you agree or disa gree with this stat ement?  Support your \nanswer with reference to the novel,  Wuthering Heights .   \n \nOR \n \n           (ii)     ‚ÄúBront √ę‚Äôs effective use of a range of cont rasts helps to create a darkly   \n   fascinating world in the course of her novel , Wuthering Heights .‚ÄĚ \n                \n                     Discuss this statement,  supporting your answer with  reference to the novel. \n \n \nB THE GREAT GATSBY ‚Äď F. Scott Fitzgerald \n \n(i)    ‚ÄúDaisy Buchanan and Jay Gatsby possess a variety of character traits that \ncontribute to the dramatic and tragic aspects of the story.‚ÄĚ \n \nTo what extent do  you agree or disa gree with this stat ement?  Support your \nanswer with reference to the novel, The Great Gatsby .   \n \n                                                       OR  \n \n (ii)     ‚ÄúFit zgerald‚Äôs effective use of a range of contrasts helps to  create a clearly \n   unequal world in th e course of his novel, The Great Gatsby .‚ÄĚ \n                \n                     Discuss this statement, supporting your answer with reference to the novel.  \n \n \n \n \n \nC TRANSLATIONS ‚Äď Brian Friel \n \n (i)      ‚ÄúThe  central characters in Friel‚Äôs play, Translations , are tragic but not heroic.‚ÄĚ  \n \nTo what extent do  you agree or disa gree with this stat ement?  Support your \nanswer with reference to at least tw o of the play‚Äôs ce ntral characters. \n \n          ",
