      'paper1': "Coimisi√ļn na Scr√ļduithe St√°it \nState Examinations Commission \nLEAVING CERTIFICATE EXAMINATION, 2022  \nEnglish - Higher Level - Paper 1  \nTotal Marks: 140  \nWednesday, 8 June ‚Äď Morning, 9.30 ‚Äď 12.20 \nÔā∑This paper is divided into two sections,\nSection I COMPREHENDING and Section II COMPOSING.\nÔā∑The paper contains three texts on the general the me of POWERFUL VOICES .\nÔā∑Candidates should familiarise themselves with each of the texts before\nbeginning their answers.\nÔā∑Both sections of this paper (COMPR EHENDING and COMPOSING) must be\nattempted.\nÔā∑Section I, Comprehending, carries 40 marks.\nÔā∑Section II, Composing, carries 100 marks.\nSECTION I ‚Äď COMPREHENDING \nÔā∑Two Questions, A and B, follow each text.\nÔā∑Candidates must answer ONE  question in Section I:\neither one Question A OR one  Question B on ONE  text.\nSECTION II ‚Äď COMPOSING \nÔā∑Candidates must write on one of the compositions 1 ‚Äď 7. 2022.    M.11  2022L002A1EL\nDo not hand this up. \nThis document will not be returned to the \nState Examinations Commission \n\n\nLeaving Certificate Examination 2022 ¬† 2  \nEnglish ‚Äď Higher Level ‚Äď Paper 1 SECTION I                         COMPREHENDING                    (40 marks) \n¬†¬† \nTEXT 1 ‚Äď A YOUNG POET‚ÄôS POWERFUL VOICE \n \nThis text is adapted from a feature article by Meadhbh McGrath entitled, Poet. Fashion icon. \nFuture president? .  It originally appeared in the maga zine section of a weekend newspaper.  \nOn that chilly inauguration day in January, \naudiences tuned in to se e Joe Biden being sworn \nin as US president, but it was Amanda Gorman, \nthe youngest inaugural poet  in US history, who \nreally stole the show.  Dressed in a sunshine \nyellow coat and scarlet satin headband, the \nyoung poet delivered a mesmerising five-minute \nreading of The Hill We Climb .  The poem ‚Äď parts \nof which Gorman had wr itten on the night of \nthe US Capitol riots ‚Äď began with the question: \n‚ÄúWhen day comes we ask ourselves, where can \nwe find light in this never-ending shade?‚ÄĚ. \nIt was about national unity and reconciliation, \nbut Gorman‚Äôs work also reckoned with the pain \nof America‚Äôs past and present, and looked \noptimistically towards it s future, ca pturing the \nmood of a country reeling from a deadly \npandemic, stark political divisions and domestic \nterrorism. \n \nThe inauguration was a rare moment where a \npoem made international headlines, showing \nhow poetry, rather th an being a solitary \noccupation or the tireso me homework suffered \nthrough at school, can br ing people together by \ninterrogating and arti culating our shared \nfeelings, fears and insecurities.  It was also a \nmoment that catapulted Gorman to global \nfame.  By the following day, she had gained two \nmillion new Instagram fo llowers and pre-sales \nhad pushed her two book s to numbers 1 and 2 \non Amazon‚Äôs bestseller list, despite not being \ndue for publication until later in the year.  Less \nthan three weeks later,  she became the first \npoet to perform at the Super Bowl, reciting a \npoem honouring frontlin e workers.",
